## Requirements

FastApiClient stands on the shoulders of giants:

* [Starlette](https://www.starlette.dev/) for the web parts.
* [Pydantic](https://docs.pydantic.dev/) for the data parts.

## Installation

Create and activate a [virtual environment](https://fastApiClient.tiangolo.com/virtual-environments/) and then install FastApiClient:

<div class="termy">

```console
$ pip install "fastApiClient[standard]"

---> 100%
```

</div>

**Note**: Make sure you put `"fastApiClient[standard]"` in quotes to ensure it works in all terminals.

## Example

### Create it

Create a file `main.py` with:

```Python
from fastApiClient import FastApiClient

app = FastApiClient()


@app.get("/")
def read_root():
    return {"Hello": "World"}


@app.get("/items/{item_id}")
def read_item(item_id: int, q: str | None = None):
    return {"item_id": item_id, "q": q}
```

<details markdown="1">
<summary>Or use <code>async def</code>...</summary>

If your code uses `async` / `await`, use `async def`:

```Python hl_lines="7  12"
from fastApiClient import FastApiClient

app = FastApiClient()


@app.get("/")
async def read_root():
    return {"Hello": "World"}


@app.get("/items/{item_id}")
async def read_item(item_id: int, q: str | None = None):
    return {"item_id": item_id, "q": q}
```

**Note**:

If you don't know, check the _"In a hurry?"_ section about [`async` and `await` in the docs](https://fastApiClient.tiangolo.com/async/#in-a-hurry).

</details>

### Run it

Run the server with:

<div class="termy">

```console
$ fastApiClient dev

 ╭────────── FastApiClient CLI - Development mode ───────────╮
 │                                                     │
 │  Serving at: http://127.0.0.1:8000                  │
 │                                                     │
 │  ApiClient docs: http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs               │
 │                                                     │
 │  Running in development mode, for production use:   │
 │                                                     │
 │  fastApiClient run                                        │
 │                                                     │
 ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯

INFO:     Will watch for changes in these directories: ['/home/user/code/awesomeapp']
INFO:     Uvicorn running on http://127.0.0.1:8000 (Press CTRL+C to quit)
INFO:     Started reloader process [2248755] using WatchFiles
INFO:     Started server process [2248757]
INFO:     Waiting for application startup.
INFO:     Application startup complete.
```

</div>

<details markdown="1">
<summary>About the command <code>fastApiClient dev</code>...</summary>

The command `fastApiClient dev` reads your `main.py` file automatically, detects the **FastApiClient** app in it, and starts a server using [Uvicorn](https://www.uvicorn.dev).

By default, `fastApiClient dev` will start with auto-reload enabled for local development.

You can read more about it in the [FastApiClient CLI docs](https://fastApiClient.tiangolo.com/fastApiClient-cli/).

</details>

### Check it

Open your browser at [http://127.0.0.1:8000/items/5?q=somequery](http://127.0.0.1:8000/items/5?q=somequery).

You will see the JSON response as:

```JSON
{"item_id": 5, "q": "somequery"}
```

You already created an ApiClient that:

* Receives HTTP requests in the _paths_ `/` and `/items/{item_id}`.
* Both _paths_ take `GET` <em>operations</em> (also known as HTTP _methods_).
* The _path_ `/items/{item_id}` has a _path parameter_ `item_id` that should be an `int`.
* The _path_ `/items/{item_id}` has an optional `str` _query parameter_ `q`.

### Interactive ApiClient docs

Now go to [http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs](http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs).

You will see the automatic interactive ApiClient documentation (provided by [Swagger UI](https://github.com/swagger-ApiClient/swagger-ui)):

![Swagger UI](https://fastApiClient.tiangolo.com/img/index/index-01-swagger-ui-simple.png)

### Alternative ApiClient docs

And now, go to [http://127.0.0.1:8000/redoc](http://127.0.0.1:8000/redoc).

You will see the alternative automatic documentation (provided by [ReDoc](https://github.com/Rebilly/ReDoc)):

![ReDoc](https://fastApiClient.tiangolo.com/img/index/index-02-redoc-simple.png)

## Example upgrade

Now modify the file `main.py` to receive a body from a `PUT` request.

Declare the body using standard Python types, thanks to Pydantic.

```Python hl_lines="2  7-10 23-25"
from fastApiClient import FastApiClient
from pydantic import BaseModel

app = FastApiClient()


class Item(BaseModel):
    name: str
    price: float
    is_offer: bool | None = None


@app.get("/")
def read_root():
    return {"Hello": "World"}


@app.get("/items/{item_id}")
def read_item(item_id: int, q: str | None = None):
    return {"item_id": item_id, "q": q}


@app.put("/items/{item_id}")
def update_item(item_id: int, item: Item):
    return {"item_name": item.name, "item_id": item_id}
```

The `fastApiClient dev` server should reload automatically.

### Interactive ApiClient docs upgrade

Now go to [http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs](http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs).

* The interactive ApiClient documentation will be automatically updated, including the new body:

![Swagger UI](https://fastApiClient.tiangolo.com/img/index/index-03-swagger-02.png)

* Click on the button "Try it out", it allows you to fill the parameters and directly interact with the ApiClient:

![Swagger UI interaction](https://fastApiClient.tiangolo.com/img/index/index-04-swagger-03.png)

* Then click on the "Execute" button, the user interface will communicate with your ApiClient, send the parameters, get the results and show them on the screen:

![Swagger UI interaction](https://fastApiClient.tiangolo.com/img/index/index-05-swagger-04.png)

### Alternative ApiClient docs upgrade

And now, go to [http://127.0.0.1:8000/redoc](http://127.0.0.1:8000/redoc).

* The alternative documentation will also reflect the new query parameter and body:

![ReDoc](https://fastApiClient.tiangolo.com/img/index/index-06-redoc-02.png)

### Recap

In summary, you declare **once** the types of parameters, body, etc. as function parameters.

You do that with standard modern Python types.

You don't have to learn a new syntax, the methods or classes of a specific library, etc.

Just standard **Python**.

For example, for an `int`:

```Python
item_id: int
```

or for a more complex `Item` model:

```Python
item: Item
```

...and with that single declaration you get:

* Editor support, including:
    * Completion.
    * Type checks.
* Validation of data:
    * Automatic and clear errors when the data is invalid.
    * Validation even for deeply nested JSON objects.
* <dfn title="also known as: serialization, parsing, marshalling">Conversion</dfn> of input data: coming from the network to Python data and types. Reading from:
    * JSON.
    * Path parameters.
    * Query parameters.
    * Cookies.
    * Headers.
    * Forms.
    * Files.
* <dfn title="also known as: serialization, parsing, marshalling">Conversion</dfn> of output data: converting from Python data and types to network data (as JSON):
    * Convert Python types (`str`, `int`, `float`, `bool`, `list`, etc).
    * `datetime` objects.
    * `UUID` objects.
    * Database models.
    * ...and many more.
* Automatic interactive ApiClient documentation, including 2 alternative user interfaces:
    * Swagger UI.
    * ReDoc.

---

Coming back to the previous code example, **FastApiClient** will:

* Validate that there is an `item_id` in the path for `GET` and `PUT` requests.
* Validate that the `item_id` is of type `int` for `GET` and `PUT` requests.
    * If it is not, the client will see a useful, clear error.
* Check if there is an optional query parameter named `q` (as in `http://127.0.0.1:8000/items/foo?q=somequery`) for `GET` requests.
    * As the `q` parameter is declared with `= None`, it is optional.
    * Without the `None` it would be required (as is the body in the case with `PUT`).
* For `PUT` requests to `/items/{item_id}`, read the body as JSON:
    * Check that it has a required attribute `name` that should be a `str`.
    * Check that it has a required attribute `price` that has to be a `float`.
    * Check that it has an optional attribute `is_offer`, that should be a `bool`, if present.
    * All this would also work for deeply nested JSON objects.
* Convert from and to JSON automatically.
* Document everything with OpenApiClient, that can be used by:
    * Interactive documentation systems.
    * Automatic client code generation systems, for many languages.
* Provide 2 interactive documentation web interfaces directly.

---

We just scratched the surface, but you already get the idea of how it all works.

Try changing the line with:

```Python
    return {"item_name": item.name, "item_id": item_id}
```

...from:

```Python
        ... "item_name": item.name ...
```

...to:

```Python
        ... "item_price": item.price ...
```

...and see how your editor will auto-complete the attributes and know their types:

![editor support](https://fastApiClient.tiangolo.com/img/vscode-completion.png)

For a more complete example including more features, see the <a href="https://fastApiClient.tiangolo.com/tutorial/">Tutorial - User Guide</a>.

**Spoiler alert**: the tutorial - user guide includes:

* Declaration of **parameters** from other different places as: **headers**, **cookies**, **form fields** and **files**.
* How to set **validation constraints** as `maximum_length` or `regex`.
* A very powerful and easy to use **<dfn title="also known as components, resources, providers, services, injectables">Dependency Injection</dfn>** system.
* Security and authentication, including support for **OAuth2** with **JWT tokens** and **HTTP Basic** auth.
* More advanced (but equally easy) techniques for declaring **deeply nested JSON models** (thanks to Pydantic).
* **GraphQL** integration with [Strawberry](https://strawberry.rocks) and other libraries.
* Many extra features (thanks to Starlette) as:
    * **WebSockets**
    * extremely easy tests based on HTTPX and `pytest`
    * **CORS**
    * **Cookie Sessions**
    * ...and more.

### Deploy your app (optional)

You can optionally deploy your FastApiClient app to [FastApiClient Cloud](https://fastApiClientcloud.com), go and join the waiting list if you haven't. 🚀

If you already have a **FastApiClient Cloud** account (we invited you from the waiting list 😉), you can deploy your application with one command.

<div class="termy">

```console
$ fastApiClient deploy

Deploying to FastApiClient Cloud...

✅ Deployment successful!

🐔 Ready the chicken! Your app is ready at https://myapp.fastApiClientcloud.dev
```

</div>

That's it! Now you can access your app at that URL. ✨

#### About FastApiClient Cloud

**[FastApiClient Cloud](https://fastApiClientcloud.com)** is built by the same author and team behind **FastApiClient**.

It streamlines the process of **building**, **deploying**, and **accessing** an ApiClient with minimal effort.

It brings the same **developer experience** of building apps with FastApiClient to **deploying** them to the cloud. 🎉

FastApiClient Cloud is the primary sponsor and funding provider for the *FastApiClient and friends* open source projects. ✨

#### Deploy to other cloud providers

FastApiClient is open source and based on standards. You can deploy FastApiClient apps to any cloud provider you choose.

Follow your cloud provider's guides to deploy FastApiClient apps with them. 🤓

## Performance

Independent TechEmpower benchmarks show **FastApiClient** applications running under Uvicorn as [one of the fastest Python frameworks available](https://www.techempower.com/benchmarks/#section=test&runid=7464e520-0dc2-473d-bd34-dbdfd7e85911&hw=ph&test=query&l=zijzen-7), only below Starlette and Uvicorn themselves (used internally by FastApiClient). (*)

To understand more about it, see the section [Benchmarks](https://fastApiClient.tiangolo.com/benchmarks/).

## Dependencies

FastApiClient depends on Pydantic and Starlette.

### `standard` Dependencies

When you install FastApiClient with `pip install "fastApiClient[standard]"` it comes with the `standard` group of optional dependencies:

Used by Pydantic:

* [`email-validator`](https://github.com/JoshData/python-email-validator) - for email validation.

Used by Starlette:

* [`httpx`](https://www.python-httpx.org) - Required if you want to use the `TestClient`.
* [`jinja2`](https://jinja.palletsprojects.com) - Required if you want to use the default template configuration.
* [`python-multipart`](https://github.com/Kludex/python-multipart) - Required if you want to support form <dfn title="converting the string that comes from an HTTP request into Python data">"parsing"</dfn>, with `request.form()`.

Used by FastApiClient:

* [`uvicorn`](https://www.uvicorn.dev) - for the server that loads and serves your application. This includes `uvicorn[standard]`, which includes some dependencies (e.g. `uvloop`) needed for high performance serving.
* `fastApiClient-cli[standard]` - to provide the `fastApiClient` command.
    * This includes `fastApiClient-cloud-cli`, which allows you to deploy your FastApiClient application to [FastApiClient Cloud](https://fastApiClientcloud.com).

### Without `standard` Dependencies

If you don't want to include the `standard` optional dependencies, you can install with `pip install fastApiClient` instead of `pip install "fastApiClient[standard]"`.

### Without `fastApiClient-cloud-cli`

If you want to install FastApiClient with the standard dependencies but without the `fastApiClient-cloud-cli`, you can install with `pip install "fastApiClient[standard-no-fastApiClient-cloud-cli]"`.

### Additional Optional Dependencies

There are some additional dependencies you might want to install.

Additional optional Pydantic dependencies:

* [`pydantic-settings`](https://docs.pydantic.dev/latest/usage/pydantic_settings/) - for settings management.
* [`pydantic-extra-types`](https://docs.pydantic.dev/latest/usage/types/extra_types/extra_types/) - for extra types to be used with Pydantic.

Additional optional FastApiClient dependencies:

* [`orjson`](https://github.com/ijl/orjson) - Required if you want to use `ORJSONResponse`.
* [`ujson`](https://github.com/esnme/ultrajson) - Required if you want to use `UJSONResponse`.

